The initial system of the [[Fuzhou dialect]] of northern [[Fujian]] is a minimal example.{{sfnp|Yan|2006|p=127}}
With the exception of {{IPA|/ŋ/}}, which is often merged with the zero initial, the initials of this dialect are present in all Chinese varieties, although several varieties do not distinguish {{IPA|/n/}} from {{IPA|/l/}}.
However, most varieties have additional initials, due to a combination of innovations and retention of distinctions from Middle Chinese:
* Most non-Min varieties have a labio-dental fricative {{IPA|/f/}}, which developed from Middle Chinese bilabial stops in certain environments.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=211, 233}}
* The voiced initials of Middle Chinese are retained in Wu dialects such as Suzhou and [[Shanghai dialect|Shanghai]], as well as [[Old Xiang]] dialects, but have merged with voiceless initials elsewhere.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=199–200, 207}}
* The Middle Chinese retroflex initials are retained in many Mandarin dialects, including Beijing but not southwestern and southeastern Mandarin varieties.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|p=193}}
* In many northern and central varieties there is palatalization of dental affricates, velars (as in Suzhou), or both.  In some places, including Beijing, palatalized dental affricates and velars have merged to form a new palatal series.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=182, 193, 200, 205}}

=== Finals ===
Chinese finals may be analysed as an optional medial [[semivowel|glide]], a main vowel and an optional coda.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=28, 141}}

Conservative vowel systems, such as those of Gan dialects, have high vowels {{IPA|/i/}}, {{IPA|/u/}} and {{IPA|/y/}}, which also function as medials, mid vowels {{IPA|/e/}} and {{IPA|/o/}}, and a low {{IPA|/a/}}-like vowel.{{sfnp|Yan|2006|pp=150–151}}
In other dialects, including Mandarin dialects, {{IPA|/o/}} has merged with {{IPA|/a/}}, leaving a single mid vowel with a wide range of [[allophone]]s.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=141, 198}}
Many dialects, particularly in northern and central China, have apical or retroflex vowels, which are [[syllabic fricative]]s derived from high vowels following sibilant initials.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|p=194}}
In many Wu dialects, vowels and final glides have [[monophthong]]ized, producing a rich inventory of vowels in open syllables.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=200–201}}
Reduction of medials is common in Yue dialects.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=216–217}}

The Middle Chinese codas, consisting of glides {{IPA|/j/}} and {{IPA|/w/}}, nasals {{IPA|/m/}}, {{IPA|/n/}} and {{IPA|/ŋ/}}, and stops {{IPA|/p/}}, {{IPA|/t/}} and {{IPA|/k/}}, are best preserved in southern dialects, particularly Yue dialects.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|p=217}}
In Jin, [[Lower Yangtze Mandarin]] and Wu dialects, the stops have merged as a final glottal stop, while in most northern varieties they have disappeared.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=193, 201–202}}
In Mandarin dialects final {{IPA|/m/}} has merged with {{IPA|/n/}}, while some central dialects have a single nasal coda, in some cases realized as a [[nasal vowel|nasalization]] of the vowel.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=193, 201}}

===Tones===
All varieties of Chinese, like neighbouring languages in the [[Mainland Southeast Asia linguistic area]], have phonemic [[tone (linguistics)|tones]].
Each syllable may be pronounced with between three and seven distinct pitch contours, denoting different morphemes.
For example, the [[Beijing dialect]] distinguishes ''{{lang|zh-Latn-pinyin|mā}}'' ({{lang|zh-hans|妈}} "mother"), ''{{lang|zh-Latn-pinyin|má}}'' ({{lang|zh-hans|麻}} "hemp"), ''{{lang|zh-Latn-pinyin|mǎ}}'' ({{lang|zh-hans|马}} "horse") and ''{{lang|zh-Latn-pinyin|mà}}'' ({{lang|zh-hans|骂}} "to scold").
The number of tonal contrasts varies between dialects, with northern dialects tending to have fewer distinctions than southern ones.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|p=9}}
Many dialects have [[tone sandhi]], in which the pitch contour of a syllable is affected by the tones of adjacent syllables in a compound word or phrase.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=147, 202, 239}}
This process is so extensive in [[Shanghainese]] that the tone system is reduced to a [[pitch accent]] system much like modern Japanese.

The tonal categories of modern varieties can be related by considering their derivation from the [[four tones of Middle Chinese]], though cognate tonal categories in different dialects are often realized as quite different pitch contours.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|p=54}}
Middle Chinese had a three-way tonal contrast in syllables with vocalic or nasal endings.
The traditional names of the tonal categories are "level"/"even" ({{lang|zh-hans|平}} ''{{lang|zh-Latn-pinyin|píng}}''), "rising" ({{lang|zh-hans|上}} ''{{lang|zh-Latn-pinyin|shǎng}}'') and "departing"/"going" ({{lang|zh-hans|去}} ''{{lang|zh-Latn-pinyin|qù}}'').
Syllables ending in a [[stop consonant]] {{IPA|/p/}}, {{IPA|/t/}} or {{IPA|/k/}} ([[checked syllable]]s) had no tonal contrasts but were traditionally treated as a fourth tone category, "entering" ({{lang|zh-hans|入}} ''{{lang|zh-Latn-pinyin|rù}}''), corresponding to syllables ending in nasals {{IPA|/m/}}, {{IPA|/n/}}, or {{IPA|/ŋ/}}.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=34–36}}

The tones of Middle Chinese, as well as similar systems in neighbouring languages, experienced a [[tone split]] conditioned by syllabic onsets.
Syllables with voiced initials tended to be pronounced with a lower pitch, and by the late [[Tang Dynasty]], each of the tones had split into two registers conditioned by the initials, known as "upper" ({{lang|zh-hans|阴}}/{{lang|zh-hant|陰}} ''yīn'') and "lower" ({{lang|zh-hans|阳}}/{{lang|zh-hant|陽}} ''yáng'').
When voicing was lost in all dialects except the Wu and Old Xiang groups, this distinction became phonemic, yielding eight tonal categories, with a six-way contrast in unchecked syllables and a two-way contrast in checked syllables.
[[Standard Cantonese|Cantonese]] maintains these tones and has developed an additional distinction in checked syllables as well as one in unchecked syllables. (The latter distinction has disappeared again in many varieties.) However, most Chinese varieties have reduced the number of tonal distinctions. For example, in Mandarin, the tones resulting from the split of Middle Chinese rising and departing tones merged, leaving four tones. Furthermore, final stop consonants disappeared in most Mandarin dialects, and such syllables were distributed amongst the four remaining tones.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=52–54}}

